{
  "doc_id": "2944",
  "text": "Interestingly, an adverse outcome of influenza and a suboptimal immunogenicity of the flu vaccine are influenced by these conditions, in humans and experimental animals ( Fig. 1) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Similar interactions between pathobionts, the microbiota, and the host are increasingly being described in animals and plants [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . In sick corals, there is a significant change in the ranking order of viruses that are also present in healthy specimens but with a distinct load for each type of virus [CITATION_8] . Fig. 1 What is a good microbiome? A typical example of the tripartite interaction between a common virus, the host, and the microbiota. a Some strains of the influenza virus cause more severe disease in obese persons or mice as well as in third-trimester pregnant woman. This occurrence correlates with a disturbed gut microbiota. b In addition, suboptimal responses to the flu vaccine are found in these populations",
